    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3181274301?book_show_action=true">Feb 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)" href="/user/show/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all">Orinoco Womble (tidy bag and all)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all?shelf=good-summer-read">good-summer-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20738920-orinoco-womble-tidy-bag-and-all?shelf=whodunit-howdunit-whydunit">whodunit-howdunit-whydunit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3181274301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15884998261016566192">Andrew Gary Stu Douglas could teach 007 a thing or two. I know Francis wrote clean wish-fulfilment Boys&apos; Own Adventures, but even for him this is a bit thick. Our Hero is even more upright than usual, and even the fact that he actually falls into a trap set by The Villain doesn&apos;t stop him. Granted, his Washington DC residents have very British turns of phrase, but his demographic didn&apos;t care about things like that. Racing has only a tenuous connection to the plot, and the girl jockey does very l</span>
  <span id="freeText15884998261016566192" style="display:none">Andrew Gary Stu Douglas could teach 007 a thing or two. I know Francis wrote clean wish-fulfilment Boys' Own Adventures, but even for him this is a bit thick. Our Hero is even more upright than usual, and even the fact that he actually falls into a trap set by The Villain doesn't stop him. Granted, his Washington DC residents have very British turns of phrase, but his demographic didn't care about things like that. Racing has only a tenuous connection to the plot, and the girl jockey does very little in the way of actual riding. An enjoyable listen for all of that.<br /><br />I remember reading this decades back, and I did remember the first kidnapping case, but the rest vanished into the mists of time, making it a good audiobook to listen to while doing household chores. No sex and darn little in the way of violence, notwithstanding the subject matter. <br /><br />Read by the inimitable Tony Britton, who could read gas meters to me and make it entertaining. Rest in peace, Tony. You are much missed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15884998261016566192" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


